      "text": "Left equidistance between West and East "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "96fb3cf4eaafb9ba",
      "text": "Left-wing Putin apologists succumb to the fallacy that a common enemy equals a friend. Universalist values such as freedom of the press and separation of powers, however, are neither \"hollow\" nor a \"postcolonial presumption,\" even if they are misused as empty words by Western politicians."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "14317364d5174b27",
      "text": "From [[Markus Liske]]. [https://jungle.world/artikel/2022/11/theoretisch-links post]\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f14a0887fae89502",
      "text": "It was impressive, the argumentative vehemence with which large parts of the German left defended the months-long deployment of Vladimir Putin's invading army on the border to Ukraine as a mere offer of talks. The more sensible ones, such as Susanne Hennig-Wellsow, chairwoman of the Left Party, are now contrite about their \"illusions, which led to devastating misjudgements, even of left-wing politics.\" Others, however, have long since resumed their favorite narrative of NATO aggression, are now outraged by the \"economic war\" against Russia, or are trying to blame the Ukrainians for the war dead. All they have to do is let Putin bring them home to the Russian empire and everything would be fine again."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "081bc2e65b33faba",
      "text": "[[Jörn Schulz]] calls these obtuseniks \"Putinist leftists\" - a paradoxical and outrageous designation. Can there really be leftists whose worldview is based on cadaverous obedience to a folk-imperialist autocrat? For whom Putin's archaic chauvinism, including the suppression of homosexuals and transsexuals and the murder of journalists and opposition figures, is only a secondary contradiction? Who consider his support of far-right parties and movements in the U.S. and Europe a clever strategy to bring down capitalism? If there were such \"Putinist leftists,\" it would be interesting to learn whether the secret plan to establish world communism they believe is behind all this is without cross-references to lizard people, child-bloodsucking U.S. politicians, and doubts about the curvature of the earth."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "05f12eb6696ae9fa",
      "text": "Certainly, especially in the so-called Left Party there are still numerous Putin apologists - even beyond the ubiquitous Sahra Wagenknecht. But since their other positions, from anti-vaccination to nationalist-culturalist hostility to globalization and open contempt for queer lifestyles to demands for an (even) more restrictive refugee policy, are also difficult to associate with the term \"left,\" they are more likely to be understood as aberrant right-wingers."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c9e86a11a83462d5",
      "text": "Undoubtedly on the left, however, is the magazine Konkret, which made a grandiose lapse at the beginning of the war. Shortly before Putin's invading army advanced westward into Ukraine, the paper ran the headline: \"Go East! NATO's aggression against Russia.\" In a statement on its website after the magazine's publication, the editorial team said, with little self-criticism, that the cover story by author Jörg Kronauer did not lose any of its substance or truth, even \"in view of current developments. Otherwise, there was neither \"understanding for Moscow's power-political ambitions, nor is a commitment to the free democratic world order of the West to be expected from this magazine. Equidistance, then, to Putin on the one hand and \"the West\" on the other? Not in this issue."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f9c2aaccb09037b0",
      "text": "From the opening column \"Von Konkret\" to the poem in the culture section, it is not Putin but NATO that is blamed for the danger of war. Kronauer, however, goes one better when he even declares Ukraine itself to be a warmonger. The latter is preparing \"the (re)conquest of Donetsk and Luhansk. The author attaches great importance to the verbal promise made by Germany and the USA to the Soviet Union in 1990, which no longer exists today, that there would be no eastward expansion of NATO. The Budapest Memorandum signed in 1994, in which Russia promised Ukraine full sovereignty and the inviolability of its borders in exchange for the surrender of its nuclear weapons, is not worth mentioning."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "234d141aa479953e",
      "text": "Overall, the argumentation seems to be guided by a widespread misconception on the left here: the delusion, born of justified contempt for German foreign policy and its representatives, who always talk about \"Western values,\" that the enemy of this enemy should be regarded as a potential friend. In this context, the demarcation of Germany's \"free democratic basic order,\" which in the statement of the Konkret editorial team is immediately elevated to the status of a \"world order,\" sounds pithy, but it leaves the question of which part of the basic values defined by the Federal Constitutional Court in 1952 is being rejected so rigorously. The \"right to life and free development,\" perhaps? The \"independence of the courts\"? Or the \"right to form and exercise an opposition in accordance with the constitution\"? Of course, if you don't need all that, you might be quite happy in Putin's Russia. But the passage is certainly not meant that way."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "107306eac65c5904",
      "text": "Rather, the point is probably the truism that \"the West\" is not the moral authority it likes to present itself as to the world. Yes, that is so. But the universalistic values that are commonly associated with it do not lose their relevance. No matter how often they are misused by Western political personnel as mere empty words, they are still far from being \"hollow,\" as Tomasz Konicz wrote at this point. Rather, they are all that stands between us and barbarism. Ernst Lohoff is right when he writes: \"The departure from the liberal-democratic sense of mission does not make the world a better place at all, but an even scarier one.\" For anyone who sees \"postcolonial arrogance\" in the insistence on a globally binding set of values, however shaky they may be, as Felix Bartels recently did in the Junge Welt, which is always warmly disposed toward despotic regimes, would logically also have to defend the Taliban's right to stone \"adulteresses.\" Bartel's instruction that leftists should primarily \"sweep their own door\" may seem to Swabian old-timers to be a species-appropriate attitude, but it is certainly not suitable for counteracting barbarism in globally networked world affairs - precisely because authoritarian ideas have long been successful in democracies as well, as Peter Korig explained at this point. Bartel's sweeping ideology, however, wants even barbarization tendencies in the West to be faded out, when in his essay he applies Max Weber's ultimately legitimizing concept of \"charismatic rule\" not only to Putin, but also to Donald Trump."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7714a10bb16626f2",
      "text": "As a (post-)Marxist apocalyptic who is quite comfortable in the hated West and who expects the final crisis of capitalism over a good red wine, one probably understands the impending barbarism as a necessary phase on the way to a free society. Its victims, however, will undoubtedly see it differently. And it is doubtful whether a left perspective is at all possible without regard to people living now. In any case, it is no good for analyzing current crises. This has been shown by the blatant miscalculations of all those who considered Putin's frequently proclaimed ethnic imperialism to be mere claptrap and, in their fixation on power blocs, were not the least bit interested in what was bothering the people in Ukraine. One could well have known - in the self-image of an \"expert\" one should even have known - that Putin's plans were not marked by the cool rationality that can be deciphered on the basis of geostrategic advantages and disadvantages. And if one had studied Ukraine in advance, read at least a few Ukrainian authors, such as Yuri Andrukhovych, Yevgenia Belorusets or Serhij Zhadan, one would hardly have succumbed to the ignorant illusion that the country could be regarded as a mere bargaining chip. Ukraine is not the post-Soviet terra incognita controlled by Nazi Nato henchmen that many on the left here have seen it as since the days of the Euromaidan. It is a country full of fractures and contradictions, but since the so-called Orange Revolution in 2004, a steadily growing majority of its society has been striving toward \"Western values. Anyone who has followed this development in recent years knows that it was not \"NATO aggression\" that provoked Putin's invasion, but the realization that this country, which he claims as part of the historic Russian empire, is continuing to lose to \"the West\" day by day, even without NATO or EU membership."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7185f09b0592f560",
      "text": "But the persistent anti-imperialist camp thinking of Western theoretical leftists seems to outlast every failure of the reality check in order to call for empathy-less equidistance between the state of mind of murderous despots and people striving for freedom and self-determination for all eternity, as long as the latter do not wave the old red flag. What currently appears as Putinism is therefore in truth only a changing camouflage for left-wing reactionary cynicism."
    }
