        "text": "Rather, the point is probably the truism that \"the West\" is not the moral authority it likes to present itself as to the world. Yes, that is so. But the universalistic values that are commonly associated with it do not lose their relevance. No matter how often they are misused by Western political personnel as mere empty words, they are still far from being \"hollow,\" as Tomasz Konicz wrote at this point. Rather, they are all that stands between us and barbarism. Ernst Lohoff is right when he writes: \"The departure from the liberal-democratic sense of mission does not make the world a better place at all, but an even scarier one.\" For anyone who sees \"postcolonial arrogance\" in the insistence on a globally binding set of values, however shaky they may be, as Felix Bartels recently did in the Junge Welt, which is always warmly disposed toward despotic regimes, would logically also have to defend the Taliban's right to stone \"adulteresses.\" Bartel's instruction that leftists should primarily \"sweep their own door\" may seem to Swabian old-timers to be a species-appropriate attitude, but it is certainly not suitable for counteracting barbarism in globally networked world affairs - precisely because authoritarian ideas have long been successful in democracies as well, as Peter Korig explained at this point. Bartel's sweeping ideology, however, wants even barbarization tendencies in the West to be faded out, when in his essay he applies Max Weber's ultimately legitimizing concept of \"charismatic rule\" not only to Putin, but also to Donald Trump."
